4. Numberless difficulties again cropped up in the fourth and fifth centuries, owing to the differences between the Alexandrian and Roman computations. These difficulties arose from certain differences in calculation and custom. The determination of the age of the moon, as it was calculated at Rome, was founded on imperfect lunar cycles. It was often at variance with that of Alexandria, which was based on the cycle of nineteen years. On the other hand, the Romans did not admit that Easter Sunday could fall, in the lunar month, before the ioth of that month, whereas at Alexandria Easter might be kept on the l5th. Finally, a tradition was supposed to exist at Rome according to which Easter could not be observed after the let of April. This limitation was unknown at Alexandria, where it might be held up to the 25th. The conflicts arising from these differences were, for the most part, amicably settled between the Pope and the Greek Church, and when Rome adopted the Alexandrian computation‚ under the form given to it by Dionysius Exiguus 2 (525), they at length finally disappeared.

5. Mention must also be made of the divergence between the paschal tables of Victorius of Aquitaine and Dionysius Exiguus. The table of the former, drawn up at Rome in 457, was not long in use there, if indeed it ever was employed, but it was adopted by the Ohurches of Frankish Gaul, and was used by them till the Carlovingian period.
